Walter Maslow https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Maslow 0 Walter Maslow (born January 16, 1926) is an American film and television actor, originally from the Brooklyn borough of New York City. He appeared as Private Marty Green in the 1958 film Suicide Battalion and as Garnis in the 1961 motion picture Atlas. In 1958, Maslow was cast as the outlaw Blackie Saunders in the first two episodes of the fourth season of the ABC/Desilu western television series, The Life and Legend of Wyatt Earp, with Hugh O'Brian in the title role as deputy Marshal Wyatt Earp. In the story line, Earp in the episode "The Hole Up" goes into the badlands to capture Blackie, who is wanted for murder and armed robbery. While Earp is away from Dodge City, Kansas, apprehending Blackie, in the episode "The Peacemaker", Curly Bill Brocius (William Phipps) and Johnny Ringo (Donald Murphy) take over the town and demand that Mayor James H. "Dog" Kelley (Paul Brinegar) fire Earp and denounce him in a written statement and pay a $20,000 ransom to prevent the town from being torched. Earp returns with his prisoner Blackie, along with his new deputy, Shotgun Gibbs (Morgan Woodward), to restore order.Earlier at the end of the third season, Maslow appeared three times as Dick Averill on The Life and Legend of Wyatt Earp, but only one episode was credited.
